article.headline: LSU 76, Richmond 53
article.story:
BATON ROUGE, La. (AP) -- The smallest player on the floor was the
biggest reason why LSU had little trouble in winning its third
straight WOMENSCOLLEGEHOOPS.com Classic championship.

Temeka Johnson earned tournament Most Valuable Player honors by
scoring 21 points and dishing out 12 assists as the 16th-ranked
Tigers defeated Richmond 76-53 Thursday night.

"I thought Temeka was outstanding tonight," LSU coach Sue
Gunter said. "When Temeka is in that kind of mode when she plays
with her head on straight and makes good decisions, she is the best
point guard in the nation."

The double-double is the fourth of Johnson's career, and the
5-foot-3 senior went over 20 points for the third time. Johnson had
plenty of help on the offensive end, as the Tigers (7-2) shot 55.4
percent from the floor (31-of-56).

"That was the second straight game that we've come out
offensively and done what we asked the kids to do," Gunter said.
"Richmond is a very good team that will win a lot of games in the
Atlantic 10, so I'm very pleased."

Doneeka Hodges scored 16 of her 18 points in the first half and
earned all-tournament team honors, while Scholanda Hoston added 14
points, the fourth straight time she has come off the bench and
posted a double-figure outing.

"The assists are a compliment to my teammates, because all I
have to do is get the ball to my teammates, and they finish,"
Johnson said. "We're going in the direction we need to be."

Richmond (6-2) looked to get back in the game with an early
second-half flurry, cutting LSU's 13-point halftime lead to 38-30
on an Araceli Gil 3-pointer with 18:47 left. But the Spiders were
quickly knocked out after LSU called timeout, as Johnson scored 11
points as part of a 13-0 run to build the Tigers' lead to 51-30.

Richmond coach Joanne Boyle was just as impressed with Johnson
on the defensive end, as the Spiders were forced into 19 turnovers
and shot 35.1 percent from the floor.

"She made our passes longer than they should have been," Boyle
said. "She really disrupted our guards from getting into the flow
of our offense."

Kate Flavin led the Spiders with 16 points, while Gil was
5-of-11 from 3-point range for 15 points.
